informal corridor discussions","Written protocols for all interactions"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most effective healthcare teams demonstrate \u003Cstrong\u003Eclear roles and responsibilities with open communication\u003C/strong\u003E. This allows team members to understand their contributions while fostering collaboration and information sharing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDesignated team leader making final decisions\u003C/strong\u003E: while leadership is important, collaborative decision-making leads to better outcomes than single-person authority. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexible role boundaries between members\u003C/strong\u003E: while some flexibility is useful, clear role definition is essential to prevent confusion and ensure accountability\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular informal corridor discussions\u003C/strong\u003E: while informal communication has a place, structured communication channels are necessary for effective team function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWritten protocols for all interactions\u003C/strong\u003E: while some standardization is helpful, overly rigid protocols can impede necessary flexibility in team communication\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuccessful healthcare teams typically demonstrate shared goals, mutual respect, regular communication, and clear accountability structures. These elements support better patient outcomes and improved staff satisfaction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Effective healthcare teams require clear role definition, shared goals, and open communication between members.","Leadership in healthcare teams should be collaborative and facilitate input from all team members.","Regular team meetings and structured handovers improve patient care coordination and safety."],"references":["Leggat, S.G. Effective healthcare teams require effective team members: defining teamwork competencies. BMC Health Serv Res 7, 17 (2007). https://doi.org/10.1186/1472-6963-7-17","Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56379"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17439"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56379"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T15:10:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T15:11:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10129"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70912"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{